\section{Design decisions taken when implementing the system, and an evaluation on these design choices.}
The key design objective of this system was minimising end-to-end latency, balancing flexibility and performance. To achieve this, we carefully evaluated which components should be implemented in hardware (FPGA) and which should remain in software (CPU/cloud). We always attemted to idetify where the best place to optimize was, when considering end-to-end latency and performance, and used our analysis on these to decided what to prioritize.

\subsection{Hardware vs Software Partitioning}

We identified that the critical path of the system is:
\begin{center}
User Input $\rightarrow$ Processing $\rightarrow$ Rendering
\end{center}

Operations on this path directly affect user-perceived latency. Therefore:
\begin{itemize}
\item Latency-critical components (rendering, state updates) were implemented in hardware
\item Non-critical or flexible components (control logic, communication handling) were implemented in software
\end{itemize}

The PS, running Python in Jupyter Notebook, handles high-level control tasks such as user interaction
and cloud synchronization. These components benefit from software’s rapid development cycle and ease
of modification—for example, the button-based interface for team selection and attack actions can be
updated without hardware redesign. Cloud communication with AWS DynamoDB is also naturally
suited to software due to the complexity of networking protocols.
In contrast, latency-sensitive operations, such as battle logic computation and video rendering, were
implemented in the PL. Hardware execution ensures deterministic timing for gameplay by making damage
calculation, state transitions, special-attack processing, and rendering, all run as dedicated hardware pipelines..
These partitioning leverages the strengths of both domains: the PL provides efficient, real-time
computation, while the PS offers flexible system coordination. The main trade-off is that hardware
acceleration increases design complexity and reduces adaptability, whereas software-based cloud polling
introduces latency and communication overhead.
\subsection{Hardware}
On the hardware, we have 2 main custom IPs:
\begin{itemize}
	\item Battle Engine IP
	\item Video Render IP
\end{itemize}
The battle engine IP performs all game state updates, including damage computation and transitions between actions such as normal attack, special attack, and Pokémon switching. The benefit of making the battle engine on hardware was the scalability it brings rather than the latency. For example, we may have extended the project so that multiple characters may be attacked at once. By adding attributes and such for more complex computations, we would have reached a point where the hardware calculations of these would have had meaningful optimizations. An extension we could have done is to make FSM for how many pokemons a player has, win, loss, turn, which would make the local processing of data a lot more applicable.
The video renderer IP generates real-time visual output by interpreting the encoded game state and
rendering relevant information, such as active Pokémon and health status, directly to the display. (explored more deeply in subsubsection{} Rendering Optimisation)
Both IP cores interface with the Processing System via memory-mapped I/O (MMIO), the PS writes
input state and control signals, triggers computation, and reads back the updated results. This interface
cleanly separates high-level control from hardware-accelerated computation and rendering.
MMIO (AXI Lite) was selected as the PS–PL interface since the hardware IPs operate on small control
words rather than continuous data streams. Compared to AXI Stream, AXI Lite provides a simpler and
more suitable interface for event-driven computation.
To further reduce communication overhead, the game state is packed into a 128-bit (extra bits for expandability) encoded format, minimizing MMIO transactions and improving overall efficiency.

\subsection{Cloud}
To enable communication between multiple FPGA nodes, a cloud-based approach was implemented
using AWS DynamoDB as a centralised database. The global game state is stored in the cloud and
shared between the two players.
Each node periodically retrieves the latest state and updates it after performing actions such as attack or
switching. A polling-based mechanism is used for synchronisation due to its simplicity and ease of
implementation.
Instead of direct FPGA-to-FPGA communication, a centralised cloud design was chosen to provide a
single source of truth and avoid state inconsistency. It also allows future extensions such as additional
players or ranking systems.
While polling introduces some latency and communication overhead, it is acceptable for a turn-basedELEC50009 Information Processing Page 3game where strict real-time constraints are not required. Overall, this approach provides a simple and
