\subsection{limitations and tradeoff}
\subsubsection{Audio Processing Design}
Initially, we considered using external APIs (e.g. speech-to-text via cloud services) to process audio input. However, this introduced significant latency due to: 
\begin{itemize}
\item Network communication overhead
\item Server-side processing delays
\end{itemize}
We would be prompting to get a number back and would have to make the result go through another layer of processing to ensure that we get what we want. These things were introducing a lot of latency so we decided the system may be better without audio-processing and decided to continue without it. Making a speech-to-text hardware IP may have worked but we ran out of time to implement that.

\textbf{Text-to-damage converter}
While we decided against implementing audio processing (speech to text), we still attempted to implement a text-to-damage converter, where the user may type a word for attack and use the damage associated to that word for inflicting damage.
Since we decided using external APIs introduced too much latency, we initially decided to explore implementing a neural network on the FPGA. While this would remove network latency, it introduced:
\begin{itemize}
\item High hardware resource usage
\item Unnecessary complexity for a limited input space
\end{itemize}

So, we continued to consider what we actually want the text-to-damage converter to do and figured out that a simple look-up table may be sufficient for this.
We compared the  latency of a nerual network and that of a python and FPGA look-up table.
For the task of outputting 1 single output per user action, the difference in latency between a nerual network on the FPGA, FPGA look-up table, and python look-up table were indistinguishable. In fact, we figured out that if we don’t optimize memory location and communication between hardware and software, a simple look-up table on python where all the elements can be in the cache may be faster.
\newline
Final decision:
\begin{itemize}
\item Use a CPU-based hash map for input handling
\end{itemize}
This approach provided:
\begin{itemize}
\item Constant-time lookup
\item Lower latency than both cloud and FPGA-based neural network approaches
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Rendering Optimisation}

An initial implementation used CPU-based rendering. This resulted in:
\begin{itemize}
\item High latency during scene updates
\item CPU resource contention - other tasks ran very slow/could not run in a reasonable amount of time
\item low FPS (〜3fps)
\end{itemize}

To address this, rendering was moved to hardware using:
\begin{itemize}
\item Custom FPGA IP blocks
\item \texttt{rgb\_to\_dvi} for video output (digilent IP library)
\end{itemize}

This significantly improved:
\begin{itemize}
\item Frame rate stability (〜60fps)
\item Rendering latency
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Image Storage Strategy}

We evaluated two approaches:
\begin{itemize}
\item Storing images in BRAM and streaming them
\item Embedding image data directly into the bitstream
\end{itemize}

The BRAM approach provided flexibility but introduced runtime overhead. The final design embeds image data in the bitstream, resulting in:
\begin{itemize}
\item Faster access at runtime
\item Reduced latency in rendering
\end{itemize}

However, this comes at the cost of requiring bitstream regeneration when assets change.

\subsection{Overall Evaluation}

The final system prioritises:
\begin{itemize}
\item Low latency over flexibility
\item Hardware acceleration for performance-critical tasks
\item Software simplicity for control and communication
\end{itemize}

This hybrid approach allowed us to achieve a responsive system while maintaining reasonable implementation complexity and it reflects a trade-off between system complexity, performance, and development constraints

\section{The approach taken to test your system.}
We split the system into parts to test the system. We split the system into FPGA to Server communication, battle state calculation, FPGA to video output, and tested these subsystems separately before putting them together. We utilized our knowledge from previous labs to use a server and set it up so that the FPGA polls info from the server and loads it into registers. We implemented pushing info from FPGA to server at the same time. We rely on flags on the FPGA and those polled from the server to do certain actions and prohibit others. Using these flags and values loaded into the FPGA registers, we do battle state calculation. We send the battle state calculation over the server and after we re-poll the state from the server, we output video according to that. 
The other things are "extensions", meaning that they are not in the critical flow of the system and can be taken out if needed.

The system was implemented using a modular approach and our testing follows that.
When implementing the system, we split the system up into multiple subsystems to later integrate them into one system.
\textbf{Subsystems:}
\begin{itemize}
	\item FPGA $↔$ Server communication
	\item Battle state computation
	\item Video rendering pipeline
	\item Synchronization logic
\end{itemize}

Testing methodology:
- Each subsystem was validated independently
- Integration testing was performed incrementally
- Edge cases (e.g., simultaneous updates) were tested using turn flags

\textbf{Independent Test}
The battle engine IP was verifiedusing predefined input states to check correct damage, energy updates, and state transitions. The videorenderer IP was tested by supplying known states and verifying that the displayed output matched the expected game state. Cloud communication was tested by manually reading and writing states to DynamoDB. When discrepancies were observed, the corresponding module was refined iteratively.
\textbf{Integration Test}
The interaction between the subsystems were checked here. This included testing communication between the Processing System (PS) and Programmable Logic (PL) via MMIO, as well as verifying correct synchronisation of game states through the cloud. Issues such as inconsistent states or delayed updates were identified and resolved by adjusting data handling and polling logic.
\textbf{Edge Case Test}
Different gameplay scenarios were tested, including attack, special attack (with audio-based damage), switching
Pokémon, and timeout conditions. Edge cases such as zero health and insufficient energy were also evaluated. When errors occurred (e.g., incorrect turn switching or state mismatch), the system was debugged and refined iteratively.
This iterative testing approach ensured that each component functioned correctly before full system
integration, improving overall system reliability.
